# 3. Scale Up Infrastructure

## Infrastructure Diagram
![Scaled Up Architecture](https://imgur.com/a/jqWvrAz)

## Description
This design separates the web, application, and database layers into dedicated servers and adds load balancer redundancy.

## Components and Their Roles

### 1. Load Balancer Cluster (2 HAProxy Servers)
* **Why:** To eliminate the Load Balancer as a Single Point of Failure (SPOF). We use two HAProxy servers in a cluster (Active-Passive or Active-Active) to ensure 100% uptime at the entry point.

### 2. Dedicated Web Server (Nginx)
* **Why:** By moving Nginx to its own server, we ensure it has all the resources (CPU/RAM) needed to handle HTTP requests and serve static files without being affected by heavy database queries or application logic.

### 3. Dedicated Application Server
* **Why:** This server is solely responsible for executing the code. Separating it allows us to scale the "logic" part of the site independently from the "web" or "data" parts.

### 4. Dedicated Database Server (MySQL)
* **Why:** Databases are very resource-intensive. A dedicated server allows MySQL to have its own disk I/O and memory, preventing it from slowing down other services.

---

## Technical Specifics
* **Redundancy:** The LB cluster ensures high availability.
* **Separation of Concerns:** Each server does exactly one job, making the system easier to debug and optimize.
* **Private Network:** In this setup, the DB and App servers can be placed in a private network, only allowing the Web server to communicate with them, which significantly increases security.

## Identified Issues
* **Complexity:** Managing more servers requires automation tools.
* **Cost:** More servers mean higher infrastructure costs.
